                                                                                                               February momentum for mobile mania
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Growth story                                  
	New Delhi, March 10: Around 9.18 million people took GSM mobile connections in February, a rise of 3.25 per cent over the January figure.        
	The GSM subscriber base in February rose to 277 million from 267.5 million in January, data released by the Cellular Operators Association of India (Coai) showed.         
	The growth in 2008 was 35 per cent, far higher than the 19 per cent seen in 2007, telecom analyst Sudipto Bose said.        
	GSM  an acronym for global system for mobile communications  is a popular platform offering mobile services in India, the worlds fastest growing market.         
	The GSM market serves 75 per cent of about 350 million customers in the country.         
	According to industry experts, low call rates because of high competition among service providers have made telecom a recession-proof industry.        
	India represents a unique mobile market where competition is highest and tariffs are the lowest, said T.V. Ramachandran, director-general of Coai.        
	Bharti Airtel, the countrys top GSM operator, added 2.7 million customers in February, taking its market share to 32.8 per cent and total subscriber base to 91 million.        
	Vodafone Essar added 2.5 million users to take its base to 65 million.         
	Bharat Sanchar Nigam Limited (BSNL), which has started providing 3G mobile services, added 1.5 million users to increase its base to 44 million in February.        
	Vodafone is the second largest mobile operator with a market share of 23.7 per cent, followed by BSNL at 15.9 per cent.        
	The data, however, do not include additions by Reliance Communications, which alone accounted for more than 5 million new GSM connections in January.        
	According to research firm IDC, spending on mobile calls is regarded as a necessity in the country. Last month saw a record 15.4 million new cellphone users  the biggest monthly growth ever.         
	According to the Telecom Regulatory Authority of India, 34.5 per cent of the population owned a telephone by January. Total wireless connections stand at 362.30 million, up from 233.63 million a year ago. Taking into account fixed line users, the country has over 400 million connections at present.                                                                                                                                                           
